## Recommended model

<!--
Each attest slash command has a `recommended-model` frontmatter field
(sonnet or opus). The recommendations reflect what each command was
tested against. Using a different model isn't blocked — it's a
known-unknown that the team carries.
-->

The attest commands recommend models as follows:

| Command            | Recommended | Why |
|--------------------|-------------|-----|
| `/spec`            | sonnet      | Drafting + scope judgment; sonnet handles this well |
| `/contract`        | sonnet      | Deterministic compile work; sonnet for re-runs, opus for first compile of a complex spec |
| `/work`            | opus        | Heavy execution across many files; benefits from larger context handling |
| `/ship`            | opus        | Orchestrator; subagents inherit their own recommended-model |
| `/check`           | sonnet      | Drift detection; sonnet sufficient |
| `/fix`             | opus        | Bug classification + execution; opus for the diagnosis quality |
| `/investigate`     | opus        | Open-ended discovery; opus for hypothesis generation |
| `/encode-lesson`   | opus        | High-stakes: affects every future session; opus for the abstraction judgment |
| `/review-decisions`| sonnet      | Presenting + classifying; sonnet sufficient |

**This is advisory, not enforced.** Claude Code uses whatever model the user has selected at invocation time. The ledger records `model` and `recommended_model` on every session_start event so divergence is queryable. For regulated use, deviating from the recommendation is fine but the audit trail captures intent.

